DSA-0301. Design Patterns (Reusable Solutions) ğŸ—ï¸
ğŸ§  Logic: Design Patterns are standardized, reusable solutions to common problems encountered during software design. They are not finalized code but rather $\mathbf{templates}$ or best practices that experienced object-oriented developers use to make code more flexible, maintainable, and understandable.Patterns are categorized into three groups:Creational: Deals with object creation mechanisms. (e.g., $\mathbf{Singleton}$, Factory).Structural: Deals with class and object composition. (e.g., $\mathbf{Adapter}$, Decorator).Behavioral: Deals with communication between objects. (e.g., $\mathbf{Observer}$, Strategy).ğŸ“Œ Example (Singleton Pattern - Creational):Java// Goal: Ensure only ONE instance of a class exists throughout the application.

class DatabaseConnection {
    private static DatabaseConnection instance;
    
    // 1. Private constructor prevents external instantiation
    private DatabaseConnection() {} 
    
    // 2. Public static method provides the global access point
    public static DatabaseConnection getInstance() {
        if (instance == null) {
            // Lazy initialization (often requires synchronization in multithreaded apps)
            instance = new DatabaseConnection(); 
        }
        return instance;
    }
}
